# Slack Triage

Read-only scan of critical channels. Surface unresolved items only.

## Suppression

Before flagging anything, consult the `note-management` skill:
```bash
python3 {{WORKSPACE_ROOT}}/skills/note-management/scripts/directives.py check "<channel + message text>" --scope slack-triage
```
If `surface: false`, drop.

## Critical channels

{{#SLACK_CRITICAL_CHANNELS}}
- `#{{.name}}` (`{{.id}}`) — {{.purpose}}
{{/SLACK_CRITICAL_CHANNELS}}

## Workflow

1. For each critical channel, fetch messages since `state/last_ts.txt`.
2. For each new message:
   a. Read the **full thread** (`conversations.replies`).
   b. If thread shows resolved → skip.
   c. Run directives check.
   d. If still flag-worthy → surface.
3. Update `last_ts.txt` to the latest ts seen.

## Surfacing format

```
• **#channel** — <one-line summary> — [→ thread](slack-link)
```

## Hard rules

- **Never post as {{USER_PREFERRED_NAME}}** unless explicitly told this conversation.
- **Always read full thread** before surfacing — surfacing a resolved thread wastes attention.
- **No DM monitoring** unless added to critical channels list.

## Tokens

User session tokens in `.env`: `SLACK_XOXC_TOKEN` + `SLACK_XOXD_TOKEN`. Tokens expire ~30 days; refresh from DevTools when `invalid_auth` returns.

## State

- `state/last_ts.txt` — Slack ts of the last message processed.
